WEBVTT

00:02.381 --> 00:05.788
<i>- ♪ Down in Carolina</i>
<i>where the kudzu grows ♪</i>

00:05.822 --> 00:08.528
♪ They're solving mysteries,
and they're being bros ♪

00:08.561 --> 00:12.368
♪ Pedal to the metal,
the ultimate high ♪

00:12.401 --> 00:14.673
♪ No second chances
'cause it's do-or-die ♪

00:14.706 --> 00:16.777
♪ In Dicktown, yeah ♪

00:16.810 --> 00:18.581
♪ It's going down ♪

00:18.614 --> 00:21.654
♪ You better shape up
when they come around ♪

00:21.687 --> 00:24.192
♪ Put the two together,
you get number one ♪

00:24.225 --> 00:27.164
♪ 'Cause they're interesting,
cool, and fun ♪

00:27.198 --> 00:28.601
Now dig it.

00:28.634 --> 00:31.607
♪ Rattle, rattle,
shakin' the cage ♪

00:31.640 --> 00:33.811
♪ Hometown heroes
for a modern age ♪

00:33.844 --> 00:35.715
♪ Put your cards
on the table ♪

00:35.748 --> 00:38.521
♪ They've already won ♪

00:38.554 --> 00:41.426
♪ 'Cause they're interesting,
cool, and fun ♪

00:41.459 --> 00:44.298
- I'm telling you, Dana,
these two jokers are cool.

00:44.332 --> 00:46.537
They're perfect
for Channel 57 News.

00:46.570 --> 00:48.641
- Uh, Taggy,
we have never fought ninjas.

00:48.674 --> 00:50.210
- Guys, look, come on,

00:50.244 --> 00:53.216
you got to put your intention
into the universe.

00:53.250 --> 00:57.157
- You must conceive the dream
to achieve the dream, rar.

00:57.191 --> 00:59.529
- Uh, okay, look,
"Early Evening Magazine"

00:59.563 --> 01:01.800
loves profiling
local businesses,

01:01.834 --> 01:03.571
but where's the human interest?

01:03.604 --> 01:04.740
- You kidding me?

01:04.773 --> 01:07.111
These guys are so human,
it's pathetic.

01:07.144 --> 01:08.113
- Hey.
- Used to be they worked

01:08.146 --> 01:10.284
exclusively for teenagers.

01:10.317 --> 01:13.089
They hired me to find
more grown-up clients.

01:13.123 --> 01:15.528
- "Works for teenagers"
was a better angle.

01:15.561 --> 01:17.431
Can't you do that again?
- Uh, no.

01:17.464 --> 01:18.668
I've been doing that
my whole life.

01:18.701 --> 01:20.203
It's time to move on.
- Wait.

01:20.237 --> 01:23.844
You're John Hunchman,
Boy Detective!

01:23.878 --> 01:26.416
Didn't I profile you,
like, 20 years ago?

01:26.449 --> 01:27.585
- Oh, yes, that's true.

01:27.619 --> 01:29.523
I-I didn't think
you'd remember that.

01:29.556 --> 01:32.428
- Oh, no, you were a big deal.

01:32.461 --> 01:34.231
What happened to you?

01:34.265 --> 01:37.104
- Uh, well, I-I've done a lot
of work since then.

01:37.137 --> 01:38.373
- All right, here's the pitch:

01:38.406 --> 01:41.446
I've lined the guys up
with an incredible case.

01:41.479 --> 01:42.882
- Okay. What is it?

01:42.916 --> 01:46.790
- The mystery of the missing
pimento cheese recipe.

01:46.824 --> 01:49.228
- Whoa.
Someone's stolen the Lunch Hut's

01:49.261 --> 01:51.232
famous pimento cheese rec--
- Wait, what?

01:51.265 --> 01:52.334
I love that cheese!

01:52.368 --> 01:53.638
- Everyone does.

01:53.671 --> 01:55.273
It's an institution.

01:55.307 --> 01:57.311
A boy detective who wants
to grow up

01:57.344 --> 01:58.614
plus cheese.

01:58.648 --> 02:00.551
Oh, this could be big.

02:00.585 --> 02:02.254
Donnie, bring the van around.

02:02.287 --> 02:04.325
We have a regional news
award to win.

02:04.358 --> 02:06.597
- Whoo!
- The Chief does it again.

02:06.630 --> 02:08.266
- I mean, Dana Singh, man!

02:08.300 --> 02:10.237
This is
Dicktown Early Evening.

02:10.270 --> 02:12.274
We're gonna be
so freaking famous!

02:12.308 --> 02:13.811
- Dana Singh is a star-maker
in this town.

02:13.844 --> 02:15.782
Remember when she profiled that
rooster that could do Sudoku?

02:15.815 --> 02:17.585
(Speaking with British accent)
- Rooster Cockburn,

02:17.619 --> 02:20.157
the Cockney rooster
of Piedmont, North Carolina!

02:20.190 --> 02:21.694
- I forgot that rooster
had an accent.

02:21.727 --> 02:23.731
- Uh, hello!
Don't forget the robot!

02:23.764 --> 02:24.866
- That's a toy, Taggy.

02:24.900 --> 02:26.469
- Yeah, whatever.

02:26.503 --> 02:29.943
Beep-boop, just remember
to look cool for Dana Singh.

02:29.976 --> 02:31.714
Beep-boop.

02:31.747 --> 02:34.753
[exciting music]

02:37.324 --> 02:39.328
- [sighs]
I feel so dang stupid.

02:39.362 --> 02:42.368
Just before he passed,
my dad, Mr. Moistly Sr.,

02:42.401 --> 02:44.673
wrote out
his secret recipe for me,

02:44.706 --> 02:46.677
one copy,
always in my wallet.

02:46.710 --> 02:48.581
I even laminated it.
[chuckles]

02:48.614 --> 02:50.752
You have to when you're working
with that much mayo,

02:50.785 --> 02:52.956
but then it disappeared.

02:52.989 --> 02:55.628
- Okay.
Well, tell me what happened.

02:55.661 --> 02:57.565
I'll travel to the scene
of the crime

02:57.599 --> 02:58.968
in my mind palace.

02:59.001 --> 03:02.474
- Whoa! Your what?
- My mind palace, David.

03:02.509 --> 03:04.613
- Oh, right, your mind palace!

03:04.646 --> 03:08.453
Of course, the very cool thing
you always do.

03:08.486 --> 03:09.890
- Shh, shh, shh, I'm trying
to concentrate.

03:09.923 --> 03:11.493
Here we go.

03:11.527 --> 03:14.465
[trippy string music]

03:14.499 --> 03:20.310
♪ ♪

03:21.747 --> 03:24.218
- Well, what happened was,

03:24.251 --> 03:25.822
I was here at the Lunch Hut
after close

03:25.855 --> 03:27.559
having a slice of peach pie

03:27.592 --> 03:30.698
and trying to solve a real
pernicious word jumble--

03:30.732 --> 03:33.637
- Okay. Who else was there?

03:33.671 --> 03:35.373
- Uh, nobody.

03:35.407 --> 03:37.746
My wallet always bunches up
in my pants when I sit,

03:37.779 --> 03:39.916
hurts my groin, you know.

03:39.950 --> 03:41.687
So I put the wallet
on the table,

03:41.720 --> 03:45.795
and when I got in
the next morning, it was gone.

03:45.828 --> 03:47.431
- That's it?
You made me go

03:47.464 --> 03:48.934
into my mind palace
for a left-behind wallet?

03:48.968 --> 03:51.507
- Yes, sir.
- For real? All right.

03:51.540 --> 03:53.677
Oh, by the way, the word you
were looking for, "cushion."

03:53.711 --> 03:54.746
- [gasps]
- How do you know

03:54.780 --> 03:56.382
you didn't just
lose your wallet?

03:56.416 --> 03:58.921
- Well, someone texted me
a blurry picture of the recipe.

03:58.954 --> 04:00.792
Now, I offered them
$100 for it,

04:00.825 --> 04:02.562
but they--
they didn't write back.

04:02.595 --> 04:04.499
- Well, you must have made that
pimento cheese a million times.

04:04.533 --> 04:06.402
Don't you remember the recipe?

04:06.436 --> 04:08.406
- I've been trying to,

04:08.440 --> 04:10.545
but taste this.

04:11.980 --> 04:15.454
- It tastes fine.
- Oh! Pff! No! Pff!

04:15.487 --> 04:17.057
Get this out of my mouth!

04:17.091 --> 04:18.460
Is this Hellman's Mayonnaise?

04:18.494 --> 04:19.462
- Yes, it is.
- Ugh!

04:19.496 --> 04:21.299
- I forgot which mayo to use!

04:21.332 --> 04:23.871
- Duke's Mayo, man!
Duke's!

04:23.904 --> 04:25.675
Come on, man,
get your head in the game!

04:25.708 --> 04:26.977
- Ugh, no.

04:27.010 --> 04:28.881
This is why
I need that recipe back.

04:28.914 --> 04:30.952
What if it gets sold
on the dark web?

04:30.985 --> 04:32.421
I'll be ruined!

04:32.454 --> 04:33.624
- Don't worry,
you're in good hands.

04:33.657 --> 04:35.828
Correct that:
You're in cool hands.

04:37.832 --> 04:39.335
Ow.

04:39.368 --> 04:41.305
Promise me you won't use this?

04:41.339 --> 04:43.042
[jazzy music]

04:43.076 --> 04:44.846
- So, David,
what does being

04:44.880 --> 04:46.884
a private investigator mean
to you?

04:46.917 --> 04:49.623
- Oh, Dana Singh,
that is such a good question.

04:49.656 --> 04:52.361
You know,
a wise woman once said,

04:52.394 --> 04:55.033
"Achieving excellence
is the first step

04:55.066 --> 04:57.772
to achieving true excellence!"

04:57.806 --> 04:59.441
- Uh, what's with the voice?

04:59.475 --> 05:02.414
- Oh, that's my homage
to Dr. Marjorie Frost.

05:02.447 --> 05:04.385
She's a tenured professor
who I found on YouTube.

05:04.418 --> 05:06.055
She's changed my life.

05:06.088 --> 05:08.326
She wrote this book right here--
[grunts]

05:08.359 --> 05:10.531
"Unleashing
the Pterodactyl Within:

05:10.565 --> 05:12.869
"13 Rules
for Getting What You Want

05:12.902 --> 05:14.573
and Flying Away with It."

05:14.606 --> 05:19.348
I mean, this book is central
to Operation Grow Up.

05:19.381 --> 05:22.020
- Oh, God, did he really mention
Operation Grow Up?

05:22.054 --> 05:23.657
- Last year,
John and I realized

05:23.691 --> 05:25.460
we never really grew up.

05:25.495 --> 05:28.534
Like, I'm still living
in my parents' basement.

05:28.567 --> 05:30.337
John was still working
for teenagers,

05:30.370 --> 05:32.107
which is maybe illegal.
We're not sure.

05:32.140 --> 05:34.713
- So David and I set
some new life goals.

05:34.746 --> 05:36.617
- My goal:
to make a lot of money

05:36.650 --> 05:38.554
and move out
of my parents' basement.

05:38.587 --> 05:40.591
John's goal:
stop working for teenagers

05:40.625 --> 05:43.564
and get his first real
human girlfriend.

05:43.597 --> 05:46.770
- No, no, I've had plenty
of human girlfriends.

05:46.803 --> 05:48.941
- Oh, no, no, no, no,
John never had a girlfriend.

05:48.974 --> 05:50.912
It used to confuse me

05:50.945 --> 05:52.414
until I read an article

05:52.447 --> 05:55.020
about people who are asexual.

05:55.053 --> 05:56.723
Wowie Magowie!

05:56.757 --> 05:59.796
I finally had a word
to describe my son!

05:59.829 --> 06:02.000
But when I sent him
the clipping, he says,

06:02.034 --> 06:04.539
"No, Dad, you're wrong."

06:04.573 --> 06:05.808
I worry about him.

06:05.841 --> 06:08.479
- I am sexual,
just infrequently

06:08.514 --> 06:10.016
and for short periods of time.

06:10.050 --> 06:11.553
There was one person, though.

06:11.587 --> 06:13.757
- Hey, John's my friend.

06:13.791 --> 06:15.494
I'm not gonna talk
behind his back.

06:15.528 --> 06:18.834
- He said he gave you, quote,
"right of first refusal"

06:18.867 --> 06:20.403
on his, quote,

06:20.437 --> 06:22.675
"offer of a romantic
relationship."

06:22.709 --> 06:24.613
- Oh, he told you that? Ugh.

06:24.646 --> 06:26.883
Yeah, I love that guy,

06:26.917 --> 06:28.554
but that was never gonna happen.

06:28.587 --> 06:31.960
- Yeah, she was, uh,
the first to refuse.

06:31.994 --> 06:33.597
Several have refused since.

06:33.631 --> 06:35.133
I will not give up, though.

06:35.166 --> 06:37.872
[dramatic rock music]

06:37.906 --> 06:39.108
- Hello.

06:39.141 --> 06:40.544
- Is that for
tonight's stakeout?

06:40.578 --> 06:41.880
- This? No.

06:41.914 --> 06:43.784
This is for a party.

06:43.817 --> 06:45.521
I'm just renting them
walkie-talkies for tonight.

06:45.554 --> 06:47.057
- So do you think
John and David

06:47.090 --> 06:49.428
will succeed
at Operation Grow Up?

06:49.461 --> 06:53.604
- [laughs]
Okay.

06:53.637 --> 06:55.608
- Hell, yes, it will succeed!

06:55.641 --> 06:56.977
Here's the thing
about growing up:

06:57.010 --> 06:58.747
even a baby can do it.

06:58.781 --> 07:01.118
I'm giving myself five weeks
to become a fully mature,

07:01.152 --> 07:03.122
masculine life warrior,
and you know what?

07:03.156 --> 07:05.093
Eff it, I'll probably
get it done in four weeks.

07:08.500 --> 07:09.536
- It's easy.

07:09.569 --> 07:10.871
If you just follow the clues,

07:10.905 --> 07:11.974
you always get it right.

07:12.007 --> 07:14.713
- You were such a star then.

07:14.746 --> 07:17.217
Does it hurt to think
about those days now?

07:17.250 --> 07:18.219
- I don't really think
about the past.

07:18.252 --> 07:19.723
I'm moving forward.

07:19.756 --> 07:21.693
- So that's a yes?
- Erm, if you don't mind,

07:21.727 --> 07:24.499
I have a pimento cheese
mystery to solve.

07:24.532 --> 07:26.637
We're here, and it's go-time.

07:26.670 --> 07:28.607
♪ ♪

07:28.641 --> 07:30.076
- So, John,

07:30.110 --> 07:31.647
tell us what's happening.

07:31.680 --> 07:33.116
- You see,
this case is personal.

07:33.149 --> 07:34.786
Only someone who knew
Mr. Moistly would know

07:34.819 --> 07:36.790
he can't make
the pimento cheese by memory.

07:36.823 --> 07:38.861
So I asked Mr. Moistly
if he'd fired anyone lately,

07:38.894 --> 07:41.465
and he had:
his nephew Doug,

07:41.500 --> 07:42.769
a total asshole

07:42.802 --> 07:44.706
who everyone agrees is a jerk.

07:44.739 --> 07:47.945
- So that brings us here
on this precarious rooftop,

07:47.979 --> 07:50.116
the night air
thick with danger.

07:50.150 --> 07:51.485
- Uh, Okay.

07:51.520 --> 07:52.789
Yes, we called Doug

07:52.822 --> 07:54.893
and claimed to be
from "Bon Appétit" Magazine,

07:54.926 --> 07:56.963
offering $10,000 for the recipe

07:56.997 --> 07:58.099
with the promise to publish it

07:58.132 --> 07:59.703
and ruin the Lunch Hut forever.

07:59.736 --> 08:01.773
- "Bon Appétit" does play rough.

08:01.807 --> 08:05.013
- Doug took the bait,
and now we wait.

08:05.046 --> 08:06.817
♪ ♪

08:06.850 --> 08:08.019
- David, are you in position?
Over.

08:08.052 --> 08:09.254
- In position.

08:09.288 --> 08:11.660
Shoving arm cocked
and ready to rock.

08:11.693 --> 08:13.497
- Copy that. Over and out.

08:13.530 --> 08:15.568
- Man, walkie-talkies are
the coolest invention ever.

08:15.601 --> 08:17.538
Oh, wait, someone's coming.

08:18.907 --> 08:20.276
- You the man from, uh,
"Bon Appetit"?

08:20.310 --> 08:21.813
- Yes, friend.

08:21.847 --> 08:23.884
I am the editor
of the famous food magazine.

08:23.917 --> 08:25.588
Here is my money.

08:25.621 --> 08:27.759
Uh, please show me
the recipe now.

08:27.792 --> 08:30.631
- Uh-huh.
Well, prove you're the editor.

08:30.664 --> 08:32.902
- Uh, how?
- Name some foods,

08:32.935 --> 08:35.306
some fancy foods.

08:35.340 --> 08:37.277
- Oh, I know, uh,
many fancy foods,

08:37.310 --> 08:39.148
such as fancy salads,

08:39.181 --> 08:41.185
rib eye steak
with garlic mashed potatoes

08:41.218 --> 08:43.189
prepared in the fancy manner--

08:43.222 --> 08:45.861
- Don't overdo it.
- And chocolate-covered raisins,

08:45.895 --> 08:49.936
but the raisins
are very fancy diamonds.

08:50.871 --> 08:53.977
[tense music]

08:54.011 --> 08:55.648
- Damn, you know your shit.

08:55.681 --> 08:58.654
[tense music]

08:58.687 --> 09:00.256
♪ ♪

09:00.290 --> 09:01.693
Money first.

09:01.727 --> 09:03.296
- No, no, no, no, recipe first.

09:03.329 --> 09:04.933
- Hell no!

09:04.966 --> 09:08.172
What are you gonna do,
magazine man, shove me?

09:08.206 --> 09:09.843
- Your subscription is canceled!

09:09.876 --> 09:10.945
No, wait.

09:10.978 --> 09:14.284
Your ass-kicking
has been renewed.

09:14.318 --> 09:16.021
That's the one. That's better.
Get back up.

09:16.055 --> 09:17.224
I'm gonna do it again.
We're gonna do it again.

09:17.257 --> 09:19.829
- Ugh.

09:19.863 --> 09:22.000
- Whoo-hoo-hoo-hoo-hoo!

09:22.033 --> 09:23.937
Another case closed!

09:23.971 --> 09:26.208
Dude, we rocked that.
That was awesome.

09:26.242 --> 09:28.246
- Yeah, I-I don't know.
I mean, did we look cool?

09:28.279 --> 09:29.716
- Uh, yeah.

09:29.749 --> 09:31.285
- At the end of the day,
we're just shoving a guy

09:31.318 --> 09:33.256
in a parking lot for cheese.
- No, no.

09:33.289 --> 09:35.628
Dana Singh loved it,
and more important, man,

09:35.661 --> 09:36.930
we saved the Lunch Hut!

09:36.963 --> 09:38.767
We are gonna be local TV famous.

09:38.801 --> 09:40.236
- We probably will get more
grown-up clients.

09:40.270 --> 09:42.274
That's true.
- That's right, we will! Beep.

09:42.307 --> 09:43.844
- What?
- Beep. Beep.

09:43.877 --> 09:45.614
- Why are you making that noise?
What is that noise?

09:45.648 --> 09:48.720
- That's the money truck
backing up into our lives

09:48.754 --> 09:50.691
to dump a bunch of money on us.

09:50.724 --> 09:51.960
- I mean, here's the thing.

09:51.993 --> 09:53.096
I'm a little embarrassed
to admit it, but, like,

09:53.129 --> 09:55.801
what if there had been ninjas?
That would've been cool.

09:55.835 --> 09:57.304
What if there had been
a cool car chase?

09:57.337 --> 09:58.841
[engine revving]

09:58.874 --> 10:00.578
- Whoa, what the fuck?

10:02.380 --> 10:04.017
What the hell is that?

10:04.051 --> 10:06.088
- I believe that is
a Polaris Slingshot,

10:06.122 --> 10:07.658
model year 2015

10:07.692 --> 10:08.927
- Is it a car or a motorcycle?

10:08.961 --> 10:10.396
- Well, that depends on the
state in which it's registered,

10:10.430 --> 10:12.735
but why--
but why is he pointing at us?

10:12.768 --> 10:15.708
♪ ♪

10:15.741 --> 10:17.879
[engine revving]

10:17.912 --> 10:19.248
Whoa, whoa, whoa, David,
what are you doing?

10:19.281 --> 10:21.418
- By the power of
Dr. Marjorie Frost,

10:21.452 --> 10:24.024
I'm commanding this dream
to come true!

10:24.057 --> 10:27.932
- No, no, no, no, ah.

10:27.965 --> 10:29.969
Ah!

10:30.003 --> 10:34.344
♪ ♪

10:34.378 --> 10:35.681
Ah!

10:35.714 --> 10:36.716
[grunts]

10:36.750 --> 10:38.887
[air hissing]

10:38.921 --> 10:39.856
- Whoa!
- Ah!

10:39.889 --> 10:41.192
- Oh, God.

10:41.225 --> 10:44.031
Are we gonna have to buy
some weird expensive jam?

10:44.064 --> 10:46.101
- Well, look who it is:

10:46.135 --> 10:49.909
John Hunchman,
Boy Detective.

10:53.382 --> 10:54.786
- Good evening.

10:54.819 --> 10:55.955
You've heard of me?

10:55.988 --> 10:57.290
- Oh, yes.

10:57.324 --> 11:00.296
Yes, sir, I have.
[laughing]

11:00.330 --> 11:02.267
- Fucking bees, bro?

11:02.300 --> 11:05.975
- Bees? Why?
- Bees! Bees! Bees!

11:06.008 --> 11:07.344
- Ah!
- Bees! Bees! Bees!

11:07.377 --> 11:10.316
- [laughing]

11:26.282 --> 11:29.288
Made in Georgia
